The collection had been dissolved at 8.48 p.m. by the district drivers of the Prussian Palaces and Gardens Foundation (SPSG), the foundation said on PNN request.
The young people then left the park.
On Saturday evening, some young people would have played rugby in the New Garden.
The meadow had been cleared by district drivers, said SPSG spokesman Frank Kallensee on Sunday.
Again and again there are illegal celebrations in the parks
In the parks of the foundation, there are always accumulations in which the distance and hygiene rules Covid-19 handling ordinance are not observed.
At the end of June, there was a celebration with about 300 people in the Babelsberg Park, a week later about 150 people celebrated in the New Garden.
Even without a corona regulation, the parks will be closed at nightfall.
Camping on the meadows is prohibited according to the park regulations, there are only a few exceptions.
The foundation has been complaining for some time that visitors leave more and more garbage and destroy protected biotopes.
In Berlin, meanwhile, illegal park parties have reached another dimension.
In the Hasenheide in the district of Neukölln, 5000 people celebrated an illegal techno party on Sunday night.
The event was broken up by the police.
Austria: Mass tests after corona outbreak in tourist resort
With hundreds of tests, authorities have responded to a corona outbreak in the popular Upper Austrian tourist resort of St. Wolfgang.
The number of confirmed cases rose to 48, as the state authorities in Linz announced.
More than 100 results were still pending in the evening.
Accordingly, many of the infected are young interns in tourism companies, but at least one holiday guest was tested positive.
Residents, guests and tourism staff were asked to stay in their accommodations on Saturday evening.
The curfew was set at 11 p.m.
"There are cancellations and cancellations here and there" of bookings, said the head of the tourism association Wolfgangsee, Hans Wieser, the dpa.
Also, isolated guests had left prematurely.
St. Wolfgang is the most important tourist resort in Upper Austria, with more than 400,000 overnight stays last year.
In a normal season, around a third of the guests are Germans.
On Friday, the first infections had become publicly known.
The head of the district authority, Alois Lanz, defended on Saturday the behavior of the interns, who had celebrated in several restaurants and could have been infected there.
"We all liked to do that in our youth," he told the radio station Ö1.
However, two bars were closed on Friday to prevent further infections.
The Tourism Board launched an information campaign to raise awareness among young employees of the dangers of Covid-19.
From Saturday, hundreds of employees, holidaymakers and locals were tested.
In addition, all guests who were in St. Wolfgang from 15 July were contacted.
The outbreak brings back memories of the Austrian ski and party resort of Ischgl in Tyrol, which was a center of the corona spread throughout Europe in the early stages of the pandemic.
In total, more than 1500 people in Austria are currently infected with the virus.
The focus of new infections is on Vienna and Upper Austria.
Premier League: Man United and Chelsea qualified for Champions League
London (dpa) - The English football record champion Manchester United returns to the Champions League after a year of absence.
The Red Devils secured third place in the table on the last matchday of the Premier League with a 2-0 (0-0) victory against direct rivals Leicester City.
The Foxes now have to settle for the Europa League, because Chelsea FC still passed and qualified for the premier class in fourth place.
In the fight against relegation, Aston Villa was allowed to celebrate.
Manchester United took the lead through a penalty kick from Bruno Fernandes (71st minute).
After a red card for Leicester City in injury time, Jesse Lingard (90.+8) scored the final score.
Chelsea, opponents of FC Bayern in the Champions League knockout round, won thanks to Mason Mount (45.+1) and Olivier Giroud (45.+4) in parallel with 2:0 (2:0) against Wolverhampton Wanderers.
"That means a lot to me," said coach Frank Lampard, who is also in the FA Cup final against Arsenal in his first season as Chelsea coach.
Chelsea's win over Wolverhampton also benefited Tottenham Hotspur, who moved past Wolves with a meagre 1-1 (1-0) win at Crystal Palace and start sixth in the Europa League.
Aston Villa won the long-distance duel with Watford FC and AFC Bournemouth, but had to tremble at West Ham United for a long time for the class retention.
The late lead of Jack Grealish (84th) was immediately compensated for by Andrei Yarmolenko (85th).
The 1:1 (0:0) was enough, because Watford lost 2:3 (1:3) at Arsenal.
The club, which had three coaches in the season, is relegated after five years in the first division.
Just like Bournemouth, who could not save themselves by a 3-1 (2-1) at Everton FC.
In the end, a point was missing.
Liverpool FC, who have been English champions since the end of June, secured a club record with a 3-1 (1-1) win at Newcastle United.
99 points is the highest the Reds have ever scored in a football season.
Coach Jürgen Klopp and his team narrowly missed the points record in English football.
Manchester City holds the record with 100 points in the 2017/18 season.
After the Newcastle lead in the first minute, Virgil van Dijk (38th), Divock Origi (59th) and Sadio Mané (89th) turned Sunday's game around for Liverpool.
"It's been an extraordinary season for this wonderful club," said goal scorer van Dijk after the game, "that should spur us on to defend the title.
It's going to be hard."
In the end, the Premier League bosses should also be satisfied.
Due to the coronavirus crisis, football operations in England had been suspended from 13 March to 17 June.
In the meantime, there was even discussion about a premature termination or a hosting of the remaining games on neutral ground.
In the end, however, the season could be played to the end without any special incidents - but as in Germany without spectators in the stadiums.
Arrests and violence at demonstrations against Netanyahu
The protests in Israel against Prime Minister Netanyahu are becoming increasingly violent.
During the night, there were violent clashes.
The Israeli police violently attacked participants in a demonstration against the right-wing conservative Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu in Jerusalem on Sunday night.
Twelve people were arrested for participating in riots, police spokesman Micky Rosenfeld said.
The police used, among other things, water cannons to break up the rally.
According to media reports, a total of around 6,000 people had gathered near Netanyahu's official residence on Saturday evening.
They protested against unemployment, corruption and Netanyahu's handling of the corona crisis.
The protesters beat drums, blew horns and called on Netanyahu to resign.
Participants in a counter-demonstration who supported Netanyahu were also arrested, the news site "ynet" reported.
People also demonstrated in many other places in Israel, including in front of the prime minister's private mansion in the coastal city of Caesarea and in a park in Tel Aviv.
A man was arrested near Tel Aviv, according to police, because is suspected of spraying pepper spray from a moving car on protesters on the side of the road.
Another man was arrested after a knife attack on a protester in the south of the country.
The demonstrator had been slightly injured in the neck.
In Jerusalem and Tel Aviv, there have recently been several demonstrations against Netanyahu.
The rallies accompany the corruption trial against the head of government.
Recently, Netanyahu has also been criticized for his handling of the corona crisis.
Among other things, he is accused of premature easing and a lack of preparation for a second corona wave.
The corona crisis has severely damaged the country's economy.
The unemployment rate was recently more than 20 percent.
The number of new infections with the coronavirus in Israel has recently risen to new record levels.
Accident near Ahlen (NRW) - Van crashes into car - nine injured - Ruhr area - Bild.de
Ahlen - A rear-end collision on Saturday afternoon on the B58 near Ahlen claimed nine slightly injured.
A motorist was with her two children (3, 5) in the direction of Beckum on the way.
The police: "Presumably she had suddenly braked because she wanted to turn".
The driver of a Mercedes van driving behind her must have seen this too late.
He crashed into the back of the car.
In the accident, three occupants in the car and six in the van were slightly injured.
Several ambulances took her to a nearby hospital.
North Korea seals off border town after Corona suspected case
North Korea has so far seen a "shining success" in its own measures to ward off the coronavirus.
Now the country is reporting for the first time on a suspected case.
Because of a first official corona suspected case in the country, North Korea has completely sealed off a major city for fear of a catastrophe.
Despite the strictest epidemiological defenses in the past six months, "the malignant virus may have been introduced into the country," state media reported.
For the region around the border town of Kaesong, the state of emergency had been imposed.
The communist leadership declared the highest alert level.
If confirmed, it would be the first official case of infection with Sars-CoV-2 in the isolated country.
North Korea has not yet registered a single infection and described its defensive measures as a "shining success".
The information was doubted abroad.
The symptoms of the disease were reportedly found in an "outlier" who illegally crossed the military demarcation line between South and North Korea on July 19.
The person had left for South Korea three years ago and has now returned across the border.
For the border crossing within the four kilometers wide and mostly still mined military buffer zone, there was initially no confirmation from South Korea.
South Korea's military, however, admitted the possibility of an illegal border crossing to North Korea as high, according to reports by the national news agency Yonhap.
Investigations were carried out on some people.
North Korea called an emergency meeting of the Politburo of the Workers' Party chaired by leader Kim Jong Un on Saturday because of the suspected case.
The "dangerous situation in Kaesong could trigger a deadly and destructive catastrophe."
Kim had already ordered on Friday as a preventive measure to "completely block Kaesong and isolate each district and the region from others," it said.
The affected person, as well as all people in Kaesong who had had contact with her, had been quarantined.
The central military commission of the party should therefore investigate the "outlier case" as well as the behavior of the responsible military unit and, if necessary, impose harsh punishment.
According to estimates, about 300,000 people live in Kaesong.
