Tim Zimmermann starts the new season with a lot of delay
With a delay of almost half a year, Tim Zimmermann will start his debut season in the ADAC GT Masters on 31 July.
Before the league of super sports cars can start regular operation, the first test drives were now due.
For Zimmermann, it was all about getting to know his Lamborghini Huracan GT3 better.
For a long time, the corona crisis prevented Tim Zimmermann from embarking on his first business trip in grasser Racing's new Lamborghini Huracan.
Under special hygiene conditions, this was now possible.
The 23-year-old from Langenargen completed his first laps at the Lausitzring and was able to get used to his debut in the GT3 car.
"There are already a few things that are different from the Porsche from the previous season," says Zimmermann.
"With ABS, for example, you have to go into the curves differently.
But it was really a lot of fun."
Zimmermann also had fun with Steijn Schothorst, with whom he will share his orange sports car in the GT Masters.
Despite being only 25 years old, the Dutchman is already experienced in GT racing and was able to help his new team-mate in many things.
"I'm not a beginner in motorsport, but every new series brings new challenges," says Zimmermann.
"Steijn and I get along brilliantly and we have made enormous progress at the Lausitzring from session to session."
It is precisely there - at the Lausitzring - that the GT Masters will also be holding its first race.
From 31 July, the 33 super sports cars will race through Lusatia.
Zimmermann, who is one of 15 newcomers to the series, knows the track.
In 2015 he was last a guest at the Motodrom.
"It worked quickly and I didn't have to get used to the track very much," says Zimmermann, who competes for the Friedrichshafen racing community Graf Zeppelin.
"The Lausitzring has many fast passages that you have to hit optimally to be fast."
How fast Zimmermann really is then, that turns out in two weeks.
"Of course, the teams play a little poker in the tests," he says.
"In the end, however, we are very satisfied and are looking forward to the first weekend at the Lausitzring."
The race in Brandenburg will be the prelude to a densely packed calendar.
There are seven races until the beginning of November.
The current state of affairs is that no spectators will be allowed - but there is a prominent guest.
In mid-August at the Nürburgring, ex-Formula 1 driver Niko Hülkenberg will take the GT wheel.
British Transport Secretary caught cold by quarantine decision
The British government's decision to quarantine Spain holidaymakers for two weeks after their return has caught the country's transport minister off guard, according to press reports.
Accordingly, Grant Shapps is currently on vacation in Spain, of all places, while his colleagues at home decided on Saturday the measure.
Due to the rising corona numbers in Spain, the cabinet in London removed the country from the list of countries from which entry without quarantine requirements is possible.
The new regulation will apply from today, Sunday, so Shapps will also have to quarantine after his return.
In Austria, the government has also imposed quarantine measures for returnees.
But for those who are just on vacation, the rule does not apply until Saturday, August 1, and was not introduced overnight.
By the way, Spain is still considered one of the "safe countries" in Austria for which no quarantine in Austria is required.
"Many ministers must have known in advance that there is a possibility of a quarantine being imposed on holidaymakers in Spain," commented Labour MP Diane Abbot.
"But apparently no one bothered to tell Grant Shapps."
Less than a month after the end of the corona emergency in Spain and the expiry of the strict curfew, the number of infections in the country is rising again.
Virologists blame the nightlife for the renewed spread.
Spain is one of the favourite holiday destinations of the British.
The British government currently advises against unnecessary travel to the Spanish mainland, with the exception of the Canary Islands and Balearic Islands, which are particularly popular with British holidaymakers.
So far, more than 272,000 infections with the novel coronavirus and more than 28,000 deaths have been recorded in Spain.
Russia: Navy Day: Putin announces hypersonic weapons for warships
Russian President Vladimir Putin has announced that on the day of the Navy in his country, warships will be equipped with state-of-the-art hypersonic weapons.
With these weapons, which are unique in the world, the combat capabilities of the Russian naval forces would be expanded, Putin said on Sunday in St. Petersburg at the Central Naval Parade.
According to the Interfax agency, the Ministry of Defense also informed about successful tests of the Zirkon hypersonic missile built for the Navy.
The hypersonic weapons have a multiple of the speed of sound of around 343 meters per second.
They are considered weapons of the future.
Underwater tropicaleo continues to be built
Construction will also continue on the nuclear-equipped underwater torpedo Poseidon, it said.
The planned sea drone is planned to destroy coastal targets.
The president, who also sailed a military boat himself, said that this year alone, 40 new ships would be put into service with the individual fleet units of the largest country on earth.
Russia has a coastal area as large as no other country in the world.
For 300 years, the navy has been reliably protecting Russia, Putin said at the day celebrated by sailors nationwide.
In many other Russian coastal towns, the naval forces also celebrated Navy Day with parades.
In Syria, where Russia is fighting alongside ruler Bashar al-Assad, the military demonstrated strength at a weapons show in the Mediterranean port of Tartus.
Ammunition was also fired there.
A video released by the Ministry of Defense not only included warships, including a submarine, but also attack helicopters and jets.
Hurricane "Hanna" reaches Texas: Help made more difficult due to Corona
Washington - The first hurricane of this year's season over the Atlantic has made landfall in Texas.
Life-threatening flooding, strong winds and heavy rains now threaten parts of the US state, said the National Hurricane Center of the US climate agency NOAA in the night on Sunday (local time).
Governor Greg Abbott declared a state of emergency for numerous counties.
The corona pandemic rampant in Texas is complicating the work of the helpers, Abbott said, according to US media.
Evacuees urged to be careful
"Every hurricane is a tremendous challenge," Abbott said, according to the Houston Chronicle.
Referring to the Texas cyclone, he added, "This challenge is complicated and exacerbated when you consider it sweeps through an area that is the most affected area of the state by Covid-19."
According to Johns Hopkins University, around 5,000 people have died so far in Texas alone as a result of the corona pandemic.
Abbott called on people who would have to leave their homes to be careful.
They should not disregard practices "to which we have become accustomed," such as wearing masks, the governor said, according to CBS.
It is important that everyone keep their distance.
Therefore, hotel rooms have also been provided in some places.
In addition, in emergency shelters should be tested for Corona.
Damage had initially only been reported from the coastal town of Port Mansfield.
Storm warning withdrawn
With wind speeds of up to 150 kilometers per hour, "Hanna" had made land on padre Island immediately off the Texas coast, according to authorities.
The tropical storm had previously been upgraded to the lowest level one hurricane.
For the coastal section from Port Mansfield to Sargent, a storm surge warning was first issued and later withdrawn.
Authorities expected a slowdown, while "Hanna" moved further inland and headed for northeastern Mexico.
"Douglas" moves towards Hawaii
In the Pacific, Hurricane Douglas was on its way to Hawaii on Sunday night with wind speeds of around 150 kilometers per hour.
However, the hurricane center expected it to weaken further.
According to the forecast, it should be on Sunday (local time) near the largest islands of Hawaii - then as a storm just below the hurricane threshold.
Over the Atlantic, NOAA expected an above-average active hurricane season this year, according to a may forecast.
From June to the end of November, up to ten hurricanes are to be expected, of which up to six could become very strong hurricanes, the authority had said.
On average, there are six hurricanes per year over the Atlantic, three of which develop into storms of great strength.
In view of available climate data and the higher water temperature in the Atlantic and the Caribbean, the probability of a normal season is only 30 percent, that of a below-average even only ten percent, it was said at the time.
US President Donald Trump wrote via Twitter that his government is closely monitoring the storms and is in contact with the affected states.
